Finally, I don't want to live in a country run by an irresponsible bunch of greedy spivs who repeatedly demonstrate their inadequacies, who had taxpayer-funded parties while those taxpayers died, & who tell us to "tighten our belts" when they want to steal our bloody trousers.

I also don't want to live in a place where we turn away refugees, wherever they come from, and however economically "useful" they are, but are happy to add to the coffers of ppl so greedy that they start wars on the smallest pretext.
I don't want to live in a place where someone struggles to get life insurance for a mortgage bc their job - a job where they literally save other peoples' lives - will eventually kill them.
The fabric of this country is so ragged and patched that we don't know who we are anymore...

The current situation is more insidious and widely spread than our government's relationships with bastards like Putin, and it's bigger than the privatisation of the NHS. It's not something that clapping on your doorstep will fix, funnily enough.

... working jobs that progressively get more dangerous and less and less rewarding. In my bf's case you can throw in the high probability that he'll get cancer... And who will treat him? A health service, a really beautiful idea, that's been brought to its knees.
Meanwhile, people we love and respect who work in this sector are left wondering if they might have to sell their houses bc they can't afford to heat them...

Not only this but it's not just the NHS. The reason why public sector funding is cut year on year on year is bc there are literal fortunes to be made for a small group of people... All Johnson is doing is following the playbook to create his own mini oligarchy. It's obscene.

Also, the main reason ppl are more upset than usual about the NHS being privatised is bc we're in a pandemic. This stuff has been going on for YEARS. It simply isn't good enough to only be worried that there appears to be a lot of shit in the room when it starts hitting the fan.

The reason I started on energy then diverted to PPE & budget cuts is bc they are all things that worry me, they are linked into a plummet in living standards for anyone who isn't as rich as Croesus, and they are all things that our government is directly responsible for.

So... I know that was a really long thread but I'm not finished... And I'm hyperfocussed on this now... So...

Emergency workers & those in the public sector do selfless, impossibly hard work, the scale and impact of which is immeasurable.

Depending on the manager (drowning in politics & admin, & probably underpaid like you) you might get average kit, provided their priority isn't sth else. But if kit is substandard & the PO didn't get, listen to, or want your feedback for whatever reason, you're stuck.

4. Management: It's a well established fact that most ppl leave jobs bc of shitty managers; these ppl exist everywhere; the PS is no exception. Effective procurement processes depend on good comms & feedback between the users & purchasing team.

extinguish the car fire (chemical fumes, yum), strategically cut pasrts of it away to safely extract & treat the casualties, make the area safe. Let's hope the gloves you have for glass management/trauma care, or any machinery/tools you use don't fail. That would be a nightmare.

Here's a scenario. It's 3am & you're a firefighter attending an RTA/fire. You eventually arrive in the middle of nowhere (the closer retained station was closed bc of cuts). Your IC decides on a course of action which (I've never done this so for arguments sake let's say) is to

3. PS PPE Supply: If you're lucky, you have a good supplier. Goods are fairly priced, quality is great, they're in stock. In reality, this is now rare. With dwindling funds the compromise is made on quality or stock. Nurses will tell you that a binbag is better than nothing.

Interestingly, we have a perfect, real-time, example of what happens when chronically inexperienced, badly trained, poorly resourced, undermotivated ppl (for whom the rewards are negligible) are deployed to do a dangerous job.
Not only are they unsuccessful; they hurt themselves.

Knock-on effects of cuts ensure that on "the worst day of your life" not only will the cavalry arrive slower, but there will be fewer of them, they'll be less qualified, & chances are they won't have adequate resources/kit to save you.
But this isn't just dangerous for the public

I'm not reproducing the figures bc 1. Everyone has Google, and B. We all know they're not good news... For us...
But essentially, and predictably, the effects of cuts trickle down, & although frontline workers literally sacrifice themselves as human plugs, ppl die as a result.

2. Operational Budget: The UK has a quaint tradition where each budget season the public sector is bled until it barely functions. Given his friends it's hardly surprising that Comrade Johnson & his crack cabinet of arseholes endorse it. When we smell blood, they smell gold.

With training & experience some risks of injury/death can be mitigated, but you have to also, ironically, be mentally & physically fit. Things turn bad if you can't process the mental challenges you encounter.
 
The next 3 points relate to PPE, procurement, realistic mitigation.

So, if you are a firefighter - like my bf - your actual life is dependent on 4 criteria:

1. Yourself - Capacity/Skill: 
My bf's basic training was a 10 week beasting (some recruits get a mere non-beasty 2). He's tough/smart at avoiding immediate dangers like incineration/maiming

You cannot tip the protective scales in your favour & use a sliver of your inadequate (given your often backbreaking, life-threatening work) salary that over a decade has been progressively pruned to a stump - in real terms - to buy your own better kit. Why? It's against policy.

I've noticed a few anecdotal trends re public sector PPE provision over the years. They aren't universal but are common in my circles. The most worrying - especially given the millions spent on useless pandemic PPE - is that typically, you use what you are given.

You might ask how PPE procurement policies work in a public sector area that has experienced £140mill in cuts in the last 5 years, where job description scope creep is rife, & speaking out is career suicide.
But you already know the answer if you don't (yet) live in a bunker.

These rates are mostly due to chemical & carcinogen exposure above the Workplace Exposure Limit (WEL). & "whilst appropriate use of PPE should reduce the levels of exposure to individuals, there are few (if any) data quantifying these protective effects".

Full disclosure, I'm no expert, generally. & definitely not on UK energy supply. 🤓 
But BEFORE Russia in 2020, Big 6 UK energy suppliers made £3bill in profit with current profits around £1bill. This only relates to their "regulated activities". (What does that even mean!?)

We have to view this as a long term problem. If standing charges on bills are high now when the weather is sunny & mild & we're all basking in the prospect of summer, imagine the scenario when the days darken & ppl actually need artificial heat & light daily in order to survive.

So how should we view these adverts? As cynical marketing strategies to con anxious people into potentially catastrophic contracts that could financially ruin them in perfect conjuction with the arrival of winter? Pretty much.

This reductivist perception problem stifles the diverse nature of humanity, and the ability to create - whether you are obliged to construct it alone, or have help (either conscious or by example) - a space to exist as the best version of yourself. At home. At work. In life.

This tension between professionalism & individuality in the academic world - although better than it was - is still an uncracked nut & wider perceptions of individual identity as controversial in a work setting go so much deeper than appearance & lazy sexist media representation.

I have 2 excellent jobs where I'm valued & respected for exactly who I am. This isn't solely through hard work; it's bc these☝people set examples which gave me the confidence to be excellent WITH my tattoos, piercings, boots, & curly hair piled high like a Restoration badass.

People like @sixteenthCgirl, @DrJaninaRamirez,  @HallieRubenhold, @bschillace, @DrLindseyFitz as well as plenty of other incredible (non-historian) colleagues/friends elsewhere.
This isn't intended as an exercise in sycophancy, but more to say "thank you", and this is why...

Although not an academic myself, over the years I have worked with & observed many people (mostly women) in the academic sphere who have carved out (of a rock-hard unrelenting bias towards uniformity) a space for their own inimitable talents. And it's been fascinating to watch.

At the same time, my admin line-managers implied - virtually daily - that (although I was smart) I looked "unprofessional" & engineered scenarios where my expertise was repeatedly given a back seat, which given the platitudes that place made about inclusivity was fairly amusing.

I have fond memories of working w. @sarahchurchwell (she still abides in my 'Top 3 Bosses' list) & her not giving 2 hoots whether I wore boots or had stretched ears. In fact she seemed to think it was cool which was pretty incongruous given general attitudes at the time.

I have had stretched ears since I was 16 & curly hair forever; I am a naturally scruffy person. I grew up on a tiny farm in a fairly eccentric family deep in the wilds of Norfolk, so pragmatism & creativity trumped neatness. I prefer boots over heels, country mud over city grime.

My brain just dusted off and spotlit an old memory: an event at the IHR & the first time I saw @DrHannahDawson.

So... Yes. I've had a fairly normal morning apart from I feel depressed and quiet. And I threw up. And my brain is quiet. And I felt a lot like crying about 3 hours ago. 
I have work to do. Not sure if I can do it.

I took my first tablet at around 8... I've had literally no desire to eat which isn't normal. I have had no caffeine which isn't normal. I felt nauseous, and threw up. Not normal. My brain is quiet. Not normal. I feel sad. Not sure if this is normal or because I was already low.
So... Bearing in mind that I am already on a downer, super anxious about numerous things and there's a suitably raging storm outside - I'm nervous.
It affects the brain and heart so if you have heart issues you shouldn't take it. It also ages you (apparently!) and causes loss of appetite.

Yesterday, my medication arrived. (Elvanse, called Vyvanse elsewhere, or Lisdexamfetamine.) I am told that I must avoid alcohol, caffeine, citrus, brocoli and cauliflower, rich foods. Side effects are the usual terrifying ones familiar to anyone who's taken meds before.

The online literature/resources for Adult ADHD are limited & a lot of it comprises ppl on social media who have no medical training. If you take it with a pinch of salt it can be useful. I've found that much of it tends to focus on "I have that!" vs "here's how I manage that"...

So after my diagnosis I was told it would be 6 months min. before I could expect any medication (I have had a few follow up phone calls about the ADHD with a caseworker who is lovely but they stop as of next week). I've been sent a few articles etc which I'd already read online.
Another is not being able to focus on long-term projects vs having long-term obsessions.

I have had ADHD since I was a child. I was also diagnosed with high-functioning autism (a fairly common combination which causes some weirdly contradictory situations - eg. being impulsive, chatty, sociable and other times being completely incapable of social interaction).

I said I would attend any appointment they could give me. At short notice. Evenings. Weekends. Whenever. And I miraculously got one in October. It was swift - to the point - and very revealing indeed.

Someone on Twitter (I forget who, but my GOD I owe them) suggested I look into 'Right To Choose' which allows you to get treatment covered by a subcontracted firm but still officially via the NHS. Going private cost over £1k. I spoke to Psychiatry UK who gave me a 1 year wait...

🧵 cont'd. 
I decided that there was no harm in getting an ADHD assessment. I quickly realised that a LOT people suddenly were signing up for them. The NHS wait for an initial appointment was over 2 years. My doctor shrugged and more or less told me it was pointless.
It's planning the days you are going to do big projects - like changing the bedclothes - with your partner bc if you try to do it alone you will invariably sleep on a bare mattress for weeks.

burn the house down (I have nearly done this 3 times). It's when you buy pretty coloured electrical tape so that the labels you have to stick on plugs, electrical items, door handles, cookers, etc, don't make your house look ugly or like it's lived in by a crazy person.

In isolation each one might seem fairly normal. I've heard so many ppl say "I lose my phone too. That's normal!" The issue is when all of these things constitute who you are, every single day. It's when your bf has to regularly check the cooker is switched off so that you don't

unfinished creative projects, the fear - utter unbounded fear - of driving and hitting somebody, my inability to leave the house, to touch certain textures without feeling sick, my emotional obsession with food. ALL of this is just a snapshot...

my incapacity to concentrate, to not get distracted, my repetitiveness, my insomnia and inability to turn my thoughts off, my endless lists which I never follow, my piles of things "to do" around the house, the rotting food in the fridge, the countless

My constant interruptions, my tempestuous temper, my crippling self-hatred/criticism, my inability to remember anything people told me, my highly-developped capacity to repeately lose things that I literally had in my hand moments before, my clumsiness,

In summer last year my partner who works for the emergency services and has - as a result - some mental health training, asked me if I thought I might have ADHD. He'd been with me for around 6 years at this point so was fairly well-versed in my weirdnesses...

I have been too scared of going back to the doctors in case I run into that GP (I made a complaint and they've taken him off the roster of doctors I can now see). I haven't collected my asthma medication in months (relying on taking very little of it) for this reason.

I was still chronically depressed but the fact that I felt like I had so many PG students' careers - to an extent at least - depending on me functioning meant that I simply had to. Without the Citalopram fog I was at least capable of using my brain properly.

After a month I was able to put a proper sentence together. I essentially had to relearn how to speak. (My team at work had no idea about any of this. I've since become a lot more open about it and they have - to their credit - been amazing.)

He upset me so much that I immediately stopped taking my tablets. Cold turkey. In October: the busiest, most stressful time of the academic year, whilst working at one of the best universities in the world. I attempted to hold my new team together by the skin of my teeth.

I spoke to my peers, some of whom had experienced the same thing, and resolved to come off the tablets - or switch to something better. I spoke to a new young GP at my surgery who told me I didn't know what I was talking about and said I had to stay on those tablets.

The tablets started to make me stupid. I was on Citalopram - the highest possible dosage. I wasn't able to form sentences. I literally dribbled. I would often forget what I was saying half way through saying it. I became suicidal.

A few years after I started working at Cambridge my depression and anxiety became unmanageable. The counselling service (who are absolutely excellent) diagnosed me with PTSD, anxiety, and a mixture of chronic clinical and situational depression. I took tablets and did yoga.

After university I had a series of relationships with unsuitable men. I loved most of them, but they took advantage of the overdevelopped sense of loyalty I have. I was engaged to a man who serially cheated on me, was diagnosed with cancer, & tried to kill himself on my doorstep.

I wrote my Masters dissertation the night before the second (and immovable) extension deadline I'd been given. My stepfather stayed on the phone with me all night, getting me to talk to him about what I was going to write. I narrowly missed out on a First (by 1 mark).

I went to see counsellors. One of them told me that maybe I deserved to get hit as a teenager. I had a series of boyfriends whom I ghosted. I developed an anxiety-related eating disorder at university because I couldn't cope with the deadlines and my executive dysfunction.

My lack of capacity in finishing assignments at school led to me getting mediocre predictions for my grades. I had to reapply to university when I took the exams and aced them, bc I'd set the bar quite low in terms of university choices - based on my teachers' recommendations.

They arguably make it worse. When I first lived alone, as a teenager, I was incapable of organising the payment of my bills. My services got cut off more than once. I'm fairly convinced that without direct debits and internet banking apps I would be on the street.

I've always been academically bright, but never able to do homework or assignments. My brightness comes from being able to think laterally and speedily. I have a horrendous memory. I can look you in the eye and immediately forget what you've just told me. Even threats don't work.

To the history: I was diagnosed with depression when I was 11 but wasn't medicated for it. I had a further diagnosis of chronic depression in my teens - the result of severe trauma (a messy parental split), but also partially the relentless pressure I put on myself to be perfect.
My 2nd job is one where I am perpetually required to be creative, and on deadline. I love it but it's hard-going and I'm tired. Overall, work-wise, I feel a bit like this... https://t.co/KHvFZoB1CX

There are academic strikes going on atm, and whilst I personally support them they have made 1 of my 2 already tricky jobs a lot trickier. Add to that new responsibilities and working practices and that my autistic brain doesn't deal overly well with change & you get an idea.

First, the background. It's been a bit of a stressful few weeks. My partner and I both had big work changes in January and are trying to keep our heads up despite things seeingly being determined to mentally stomp on us. We both have stressful jobs.

It's unhelpful to underestimate the capacity of ppl with ND conditions to literally unpick and question every aspect of life even down to the tiniest detail. It can be totally mentally crippling.

It's often not as simple as petting the dog. Could be that you feel compelled to pet the dog in order to seem sociable (& not like a psychopath which for some reason you think you do). Maybe dogs are something that you have a fixation on. It may be that they calm you down.

Of COURSE balance/critical thinking are required when one is obliged to self-manage mh conditions/find one's own way in the dark bc mh services are totally screwed - but it's shortsighted to simplify thought processes like this if you have no concept of the condition itself. https://t.co/eZjjaT40Pi

@sannewman Then there's the overthinking aspect which affects a lot of ppl with ADHD/autism and leads to this kind of microexamination. One has to take those communities with a pinch of salt but to those who've just been handed a diagnosis & then literally zero support there is value there.

@sannewman Also, there's a difference between saying you lose your keys a lot & losing them 15 times a day. Giving a specific number count of times one loses one's keys makes one sound MORE autistic. But people don't understand the frequency if you just say "a lot".

@sannewman Maybe it's bc with later diagnoses you question almost every decision/behaviour bc the diagnosis can feel like having the rug pulled out from under your feet. A lot of the traits are ones that you considered completely normal. So it's just ppl readjusting their compass.

When did shouting the loudest and coming up with the most outrageous lie become something that anyone gave their time to?

I see so many social media posts of my friends going to the pub or shouting about how vaccines are dangerous. What we need - if there is to be debate (though seriously - why would you question people like Whitty or IndySage?) - is the rebuilding of reasoned factual interaction.
If this kind of safeguard is the only thing that we implement for future generations we could at least have been shown to have done something responsible with whatever power we have as individuals.

NEEDS to be heard by your Average Joe. And MPs who try to dissemble and prevent this in order to pursue their own agenda - not just in this case, but as has been so obviously shown in others should be heavily sanctioned.

What I mean to say is that expertise and professional advice (and let us remember that Whitty's isn't just his own - it is honed from years of experience & expertise pulled from teams across the country and internationally who have spent their careers working for the public good)

This is why it's not just dangerous that MPs like Joy Morrissey feel they have the right to use their platform to demand censorship of experts like Whitty, but that level of irresponsibility and cynical dissemblance is unbecoming of a member of Parliament.

I wonder what these people who still vote Conservative get from it? The power of being right is potent, sure... But they aren't... Perhaps it's the fact that they are finally being listened to, and their warped narratives given credence by people who don't know any better.

Our government haven't made the right choices. At all. Not for the wellbeing, sanity, prosperity of our country. I cannot point to a single vote or piece of legislation being passed as being a positive move for literally anybody I know. And I try to find the good in things.

My point is that all of us make choices on the information available to us, whether we work at the local chippy or we are the PM. It's a fairly simple equation. The difference is that MPs make those choices with more information, expertly put together, & they do it on our behalf.

I can barely bring myself to write that phrase because it was so obviously at the time, and remains such a cynically horrendous example of spin, a snake oil conconction to people who were desperate for some respite from the awfulness, Danegeld to the RW crackpot lizards.

But what really gets me is that some people, whether out of a sense of misguided (and I use that word specifically because irresponsible misinformation is tragically a significant factor here) hope, or delusion, thought that this pandemic would be over after 'Freedom Day'.
But the majority of us don't really know that much about viral load, modelling, and vaccines. Or even basic healthcare principles adopted by our health services. We're lucky in that sense.

Very few people I know are epidemiologists. Sure, like most of us, I know people who work in healthcare, most of whom - whatever their area of expertise - are grimly trying to get on with things despite overwhelming pressure and fairly awful odds...

Our feedback didn't suffer greatly (it actually improved in some cases) and we learned a lot about blended learning, what works, and what doesn't - over the past 2 years.
The thing that's really struck me, though, is this...

So... I said to people in September "there will be another variant. There will be another lockdown. And it will happen in time for Christmas" so at work we did our best to minimise in-person contact - we were obstinate & created the flexibility to be able to do more than most.
